You see how, with Pliny, Josephus joins the region of Decapolis to the side of Syria, and how he reckons Gadara and Hippo sor Decapolitan towns with him. And yet, as we said, Pliny doth not please usin all: but that which in him might seem most ridiculous and absurd‚ namely, that he reckons Scythopolis, which is beyond Jordan, with the other cities plesseth me most of all. For from that very city we are certified what were the other cities, and why they were of such singular name and note: having first taken notice os the condition of Scythopolis, it will be more easy to judge os the rest.
